05245nam a22006615i 9781474470261DE-B159720220306030904.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220306t20222009stk    fo  d z      eng d  a97814744702617 a10.1515/97814744702612doi  a(DE-B1597)616423  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  astkcGB-SCT 7aLIT0000002bisacsh04a811.32221 aLeypoldt, Günter, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aCultural Authority in the Age of Whitman :bA Transatlantic Perspective /cGünter Leypoldt. 1aEdinburgh : bEdinburgh University Press, c[2022] 4c©2009  a1 online resource (312 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aEdinburgh Studies in Transatlantic Literatures : ESTLI00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tPREFACE -- tACKNOWLEDGMENTS -- tINTRODUCTION: WHITMAN AND THE ‘LAWLESS MUSIC’ OF AMERICAN CULTURE -- tTransnational Contexts of Nineteenth-Century US Discourse -- tCHAPTER 1 THE NINETEENTH-CENTURY INTELLECTUAL FIELD -- tCHAPTER 2 US DISCOURSE AND THE EXPRESSIVIST TURN -- tRepresentative Authors -- tCHAPTER 3 THE POET AS ORPHIC SINGER: RALPH WALDO EMERSON -- tCHAPTER 4 WALT WHITMAN AND THE POETRY OF THE FUTURE -- tConceptual Fields of US Culture -- tCHAPTER 5 THE MUSIC OF AMERICA -- tChapter 6 NATIONAL IDENTITY AND THE SMELL OF THE WOODS -- tChapter 7 THE DEMOCRATIC MUSE -- tInventing whitmanian authority -- tChapter 8 CONTEMPORARY RECEPTION -- tChapter 9 WHITMAN AMONG THE MODERNS -- tEPILOG: AFTER THE AMERICAN RENAISSANCE -- tBIBLIOGRAPHY -- tINDEX0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aGBS_insertPreviewButtonPopup('ISBN:9780748635740);Cultural Authority in the Age of Whitman deals with narratives of cultural legitimation in nineteenth-century US literature, in a transatlantic context. Exploring how literary professionalism shapes romantic and modern cultural space, Leypoldt traces the nineteenth-century fusion of poetic radicalism with cultural nationalism from its beginnings in transatlantic early romanticism, to the poetry and poetics of Walt Whitman, and Whitman's modernist reinvention as an icon of a native avant-garde.Whitman made cultural nationalism compatible with the rhetorical needs of professional authorship by trying to hold national authenticity and literary authority in a single poetic vision. Yet the notion that his 'language experiment' transformed essential democratic experience into a genuine American aesthetics also owes much to Whitman's retrospective canonization. What Leypoldt calls Whitmanian authority is thus a transatlantic and transhistorical discursive construct that can be approached from four angles: this book begins with an overview of transatlantic contexts such as the 19th-century literary field (Bourdieu) and the romantic turn to expressivism (Taylor); a detailed analysis of how Whitman's positions develop from the intellectual habitus and cultural criticism of Ralph Waldo Emerson follows, and in a third section Whitmanian authority is located within three conceptual fields that function as contact zones for European and American theories of culture: romantic notions of national style as a kind of music; place-centered concepts of national aesthetics; and traditional ideas about the aesthetic effects of democratic institutions. The final section, on Whitman's reinvention between the 1870s and the 1940s, discusses how the heterogeneous nineteenth-century perceptions of Whitman's work were streamlined into a modernist version of Whitman's nationalist program."  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2022) 0aAmerican poetryy19th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aWhitman, Walt,d1819-1892xInfluence. 4aLiterary Studies. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEdi